    <title>Combined summary - Adjusted difficulty depending on relative blocksize</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T19:29:43.460291+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/010209.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Discussions surrounding blockchain technology have revolved around the size of blocks and their impact on transactions. One proposal suggested to tackle this issue was offering rewards for smaller block sizes, which could reduce the time-frame of the effect to a single block interval. However, this did not eliminate the need for a hard cap, and additional rules for adjusting block size added more complexity than other schemes under consideration.On the Bitcoin Development mailing list in August 2015, Jakob Rönnbäck proposed adjusting the difficulty of individual blocks based on their size relative to the average block size of the previous period. This would encourage miners to create blocks as close to 1MB as possible, which was the limit at the time. However, concerns were raised about longer confirmation times and potential attacks on the system. Anthony Towns responded by suggesting that dynamically adjusting the maximum block size would be simpler than implementing Rönnbäck's suggestion. Greg Maxwell and Mark Friedenbach's flexcap proposal, relating to this idea, was discussed on the list back in May. Questions were raised regarding the impact of changing the money supply schedule and the effect on miners who invest in equipment to mine the blocks. Tom Harding raised a concern about the "flexcap" proposal, stating that any change in difficulty that is not in response to observed block production rate will unavoidably change the money supply schedule. Adam Back referred to the flexcap proposal, which discussed the feasibility of adapting Bitcoin's proof-of-work algorithm to allow for a dynamic block size limit. The discussion continued on the bitcoin-dev mailing list, which is a platform for developers to debate technical issues concerning Bitcoin. While there are various ways to address block size and related issues in blockchain technology, each option comes with its own set of complexities and considerations. It will be important to carefully evaluate and weigh the pros and cons of each proposed solution before implementing any significant changes to the blockchain ecosystem.</summary>
